# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pcb-layout-embedded
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/copper-pour] In electronics, the term **copper pour** refers to an area on a printed circuit board filled with copper (the metal used to make connections in printed circuit boards).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/copper-pour] Copper pour is commonly used to create a ground plane.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/copper-pour] Another reason for using copper pour is to reduce the amount of etching fluid used during manufacturing.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/copper-pour] A distinctive feature of copper pour is the *backoff* (or *stand-off*) - a certain distance between the copper pour and any tracks or pads not belonging to the same electrical net.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/copper-pour] A copper pour therefore looks like it flows around other components, with the exception of pads which are connected to the copper pour using thermal connections.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/copper-pour] Many early PCBs have a "hatched copper pour", sometimes called a "cherry pie lattice".
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/copper-pour] PCB designers today almost always use completely solid areas of copper pour that completely cover the remaining area outside those tracks, pads, and stand-off regions.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/copper-pour] While solid copper pour provides better resistive characteristics, hatched copper pour is used to balance the heat and dilatation on both sides of the board in order to avoid warping of certain substrate.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/copper-pour] Heating might cause gas bubbles between solid copper pour and certain substrates.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/copper-pour] Furthermore, it might be possible to adjust the impedance of high frequency traces by using hatched copper pour in order to reach better signal quality.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] In electronics, a **decoupling capacitor** is a capacitor used to decouple (i.e. prevent electrical energy from transferring to) one part of a circuit from another.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Noise caused by other circuit elements is shunted through the capacitor, reducing its effect on the rest of the circuit.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] For higher frequencies, an alternative name is **bypass capacitor** as it is used to bypass the power supply or other high-impedance component of a circuit.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Active devices of an electronic system (e.g. transistors, integrated circuits, vacuum tubes) are connected to their power supplies through conductors with finite resistance and inductance.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] If the current drawn by an active device changes, the voltage drop from the power supply to the device will also change due to these impedances.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] A decoupling capacitor provides a bypass path for transient currents, instead of flowing through the common impedance.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] The decoupling capacitor works as the device’s local energy storage.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] The capacitor is placed between the power line and the ground to the circuit the current is to be provided.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] a voltage drop between a power line and the ground results in a current drawn out from the capacitor to the circuit.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] When capacitance C is large enough, sufficient current is supplied to maintain an acceptable range of voltage drop.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] The capacitor stores a small amount of energy that can compensate for the voltage drop in the power supply conductors to the capacitor.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] To reduce undesired parasitic equivalent series inductance, small and large capacitors are often placed in parallel, adjacent to individual integrated circuits (see § Placement).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] In digital circuits, decoupling capacitors also help prevent radiation of electromagnetic interference from relatively long circuit traces due to rapidly changing power supply currents.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Decoupling capacitors alone may not suffice in such cases as a high-power amplifier stage with a low-level pre-amplifier coupled to it.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Care must be taken in the layout of circuit conductors so that heavy current at one stage does not produce power supply voltage drops that affect other stages.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] This may require re-routing printed circuit board traces to segregate circuits, or the use of a ground plane to improve the stability of power supply.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] A bypass capacitor is often used to decouple a subcircuit from AC signals or voltage spikes on a power supply or other line.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] A bypass capacitor can shunt energy from those signals, or transients, past the subcircuit to be decoupled, right to the return path.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] For a power supply line, a bypass capacitor from the supply voltage line to the power supply return (neutral) would be used.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] High frequencies and transient currents can flow through a capacitor to circuit ground instead of to the harder path of the decoupled circuit, but DC cannot go through the capacitor and continues to the decoupled circuit.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Another kind of decoupling is stopping a portion of a circuit from being affected by switching that occurs in another portion of the circuit.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Switching in subcircuit A may cause fluctuations in the power supply or other electrical lines, but you do not want subcircuit B, which has nothing to do with that switching, to be affected.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] A decoupling capacitor can decouple subcircuits A and B so that B doesn't see any effects of the switching.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] In a subcircuit, switching will change the load current drawn from the source.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Typical power supply lines show inherent inductance, which results in a slower response to changes in current.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] The supply voltage will drop across these parasitic inductances for as long as the switching event occurs.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] This transient voltage drop would be seen by other loads as well if the inductance between two loads is much lower compared to the inductance between the loads and the output of the power supply.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] To decouple other subcircuits from the effect of the sudden current demand, a decoupling capacitor can be placed in parallel with the subcircuit, across its supply voltage lines.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] When switching occurs in the subcircuit, the capacitor supplies the transient current.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Ideally, by the time the capacitor runs out of charge, the switching event has finished, so that the load can draw full current at normal voltage from the power supply and the capacitor can recharge.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] The best way to reduce switching noise is to design a PCB as a giant capacitor by sandwiching the power and ground planes across a dielectric material.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Sometimes parallel combinations of capacitors are used to improve response.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] This is because real capacitors have parasitic inductance, which causes the impedance to deviate from that of an ideal capacitor at higher frequencies.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Transient load decoupling as described above is needed when there is a large load that gets switched quickly.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] The parasitic inductance in every (decoupling) capacitor may limit the suitable capacity and influence the appropriate type if switching occurs very fast.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Logic circuits tend to do sudden switching (an ideal logic circuit would switch from low voltage to high voltage instantaneously, with no middle voltage ever observable).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] So logic circuit boards often have a decoupling capacitor close to each logic IC connected from each power supply connection to a nearby ground.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] These capacitors decouple every IC from every other IC in terms of supply voltage dips.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] These capacitors are often placed at each power source as well as at each analog component in order to ensure that the supplies are as steady as possible.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Otherwise, an analog component with a poor power supply rejection ratio (PSRR) will copy fluctuations in the power supply onto its output.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] In these applications, the decoupling capacitors are often called *bypass capacitors* to indicate that they provide an alternate path for high-frequency signals that would otherwise cause the normally steady supply voltage to change.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Those components that require quick injections of current can *bypass* the power supply by receiving the current from the nearby capacitor.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Hence, the slower power supply connection is used to charge these capacitors, and the capacitors actually provide large quantities of high-availability current.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] A transient load decoupling capacitor is placed as close as possible to the device causing the transient.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] This minimizes the amount of line inductance and series resistance between the decoupling capacitor and the device.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] The longer the conductor between the capacitor and the device, the more inductance is present.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] Since capacitors differ in their high-frequency characteristics, decoupling commonly involves the use of a combination of capacitors.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] For example in logic circuits, a common arrangement is ~100 nF ceramic per logic IC (multiple ones for complex ICs), combined with electrolytic or tantalum capacitor(s).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/decoupling-capacitor] These photos show old printed circuit boards with through-hole capacitors, where as modern boards typically have tiny surface-mount capacitors.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] PCBs are used to connect or "wire" components to one another in an electronic circuit.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Electrical components may be fixed to conductive pads on the outer layers, generally by soldering, which both electrically connects and mechanically fastens the components to the board.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Another manufacturing process adds vias, metal-lined drilled holes that enable electrical interconnections between conductive layers, to boards with more than a single side.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit boards are used in nearly all electronic products today.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Alternatives to PCBs include wire wrap and point-to-point construction, both once popular but now rarely used.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] PCBs require additional design effort to lay out the circuit, but manufacturing and assembly can be automated.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Electronic design automation software is available to do much of the work of layout.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Mass-producing circuits with PCBs is cheaper and faster than with other wiring methods, as components are mounted and wired in one operation.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Large numbers of PCBs can be fabricated at the same time, and the layout has to be done only once.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] PCBs can also be made manually in small quantities, with reduced benefits.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] PCBs can be single-sided (one copper layer), double-sided (two copper layers on both sides of one substrate layer), or multi-layer (stacked layers of substrate with copper plating sandwiched between each and on the outside layers).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Multi-layer PCBs provide much higher component density, because circuit traces on the inner layers would otherwise take up surface space between components.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The rise in popularity of multilayer PCBs with more than two, and especially with more than four, copper planes was concurrent with the adoption of surface-mount technology.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] However, multilayer PCBs make repair, analysis, and field modification of circuits much more difficult and usually impractical.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The world market for bare PCBs exceeded US$60.2 billion in 2014, and was estimated at $80.33 billion in 2024, forecast to be $96.57 billion for 2029, growing at 4.87% per annum.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Before the development of printed circuit boards, electrical and electronic circuits were wired point-to-point on a chassis.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Typically, the chassis was a sheet metal frame or pan, sometimes with a wooden bottom.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Components were attached to the chassis, usually by insulators when the connecting point on the chassis was metal, and then their leads were connected directly or with jumper wires by soldering, or sometimes using crimp connectors, wire connector lugs on screw terminals, or other methods.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Circuits were large, bulky, heavy, and relatively fragile (even discounting the breakable glass envelopes of the vacuum tubes that were often included in the circuits), and production was labor-intensive, so the products were expensive.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Development of the methods used in modern printed circuit boards started early in the 20th century.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] In 1903, a German inventor, Albert Hanson, described flat foil conductors laminated to an insulating board, in multiple layers.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Thomas Edison experimented with chemical methods of plating conductors onto linen paper in 1904.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Arthur Berry in 1913 patented a print-and-etch method in the UK, and in the United States Max Schoop obtained a patent to flame-spray metal onto a board through a patterned mask.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Charles Ducas in 1925 patented a method of electroplating circuit patterns.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Predating the printed circuit invention, and similar in spirit, was John Sargrove's 1936–1947 Electronic Circuit Making Equipment (ECME) that sprayed metal onto a Bakelite plastic board.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The ECME could produce three radio boards per minute.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The Austrian engineer Paul Eisler invented the printed circuit as part of a radio set while working in the UK around 1936.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] In 1941 a multi-layer printed circuit was used in German magnetic influence naval mines.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Around 1943 the United States began to use the technology on a large scale to make proximity fuzes for use in World War II.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Such fuzes required an electronic circuit that could withstand being fired from a gun, and could be produced in quantity.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The Centralab Division of Globe Union submitted a proposal using thick-film technology which met the requirements.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] A ceramic plate would be screenprinted with metallic paint for conductors and carbon material for resistors, with ceramic disc capacitors and subminiature vacuum tubes soldered in place.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The technique proved viable, and the resulting patent on the process, which was classified by the U.S.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] It was not until 1984 that the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) awarded Harry W.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Rubinstein its Cledo Brunetti Award for early key contributions to the development of printed components and conductors on a common insulating substrate.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Rubinstein was honored in 1984 by his alma mater, the University of Wisconsin-Madison, for his innovations in the technology of printed electronic circuits and the fabrication of capacitors.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] This invention also represents a step in the development of integrated circuit technology, as not only wiring but also passive components were fabricated on the ceramic substrate.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] In 1948, the US released the invention for commercial use.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuits did not become commonplace in consumer electronics until the mid-1950s, after the *Auto-Sembly* process was developed by the United States Army.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] At around the same time in the UK work along similar lines was carried out by Geoffrey Dummer, then at the RRDE.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Motorola was an early leader in bringing the process into consumer electronics, announcing in August 1952 the adoption of "plated circuits" in home radios after six years of research and a $1M investment.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Motorola soon began using its trademarked term for the process, PLAcir, in its consumer radio advertisements.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Hallicrafters released its first "foto-etch" printed circuit product, a clock-radio, on November 1, 1952.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Even as circuit boards became available, the point-to-point chassis construction method remained in common use in industry (such as TV and hi-fi sets) into at least the late 1960s.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit boards were introduced to reduce the size, weight, and cost of parts of the circuitry.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] In 1960, a small consumer radio receiver might be built with all its circuitry on one circuit board, but a TV set would probably contain one or more circuit boards.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Originally, every electronic component had wire leads, and a PCB had holes drilled for each wire of each component.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The component leads were then inserted through the holes and soldered to the copper PCB traces.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] This method of assembly is called *through-hole* construction.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Danko of the United States Army Signal Corps developed the *Auto-Sembly* process in which component leads were inserted into a copper foil interconnection pattern and dip soldered.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The patent they obtained in 1956 was assigned to the U.S.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] With the development of board lamination and etching techniques, this concept evolved into the standard printed circuit board fabrication process in use today.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Soldering could be done automatically by passing the board over a ripple, or wave, of molten solder in a wave-soldering machine.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] However, the wires and holes are inefficient since drilling holes is expensive and consumes drill bits and the protruding wires are cut off and discarded.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Since the 1980s, surface mount parts have increasingly replaced through-hole components, enabling smaller boards and lower production costs, but making repairs more challenging.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] In the 1990s the use of multilayer surface boards became more frequent.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] As a result, size was further minimized and both flexible and rigid PCBs were incorporated in different devices.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] In 1995 PCB manufacturers began using microvia technology to produce High-Density Interconnect (HDI) PCBs.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Recent advances in 3D printing have meant that there are several new techniques in PCB creation.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] 3D printed electronics (PEs) can be utilized to print items layer by layer and subsequently the item can be printed with a liquid ink that contains electronic functionalities.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] HDI (High Density Interconnect) technology allows for a denser design on the PCB and thus potentially smaller PCBs with more traces and components in a given area.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] As a result, the paths between components can be shorter.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] HDIs use blind/buried vias, or a combination that includes microvias.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] With multi-layer HDI PCBs the interconnection of several vias stacked on top of each other (stacked vías, instead of one deep buried via) can be made stronger, thus enhancing reliability in all conditions.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The most common applications for HDI technology are computer and mobile phone components as well as medical equipment and military communication equipment.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] A 4-layer HDI microvia PCB is equivalent in quality to an 8-layer through-hole PCB, so HDI technology can reduce costs.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] HDI PCBs are often made using build-up film such as ajinomoto build-up film, which is also used in the production of flip chip packages.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Some PCBs have optical waveguides, similar to optical fibers built on the PCB.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] A basic PCB consists of a flat sheet of insulating material and a layer of copper foil, laminated to the substrate.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Chemical etching divides the copper into separate conducting lines called tracks or *circuit traces*, pads for connections, vias to pass connections between layers of copper, and features such as solid conductive areas for electromagnetic shielding or other purposes.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The tracks function as wires fixed in place, and are insulated from each other by air and the board substrate material.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The surface of a PCB may have a coating that protects the copper from corrosion and reduces the chances of solder shorts between traces or undesired electrical contact with stray bare wires.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] For its function in helping to prevent solder shorts, the coating is called solder resist or solder mask.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The pattern to be etched into each copper layer of a PCB is called the "artwork".
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The etching is usually done using photoresist which is coated onto the PCB, then exposed to light projected in the pattern of the artwork.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The resist material protects the copper from dissolution into the etching solution.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] A PCB design can be mass-reproduced in a way similar to the way photographs can be mass-duplicated from film negatives using a photographic printer.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] FR-4 glass epoxy is the most common insulating substrate.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Another substrate material is cotton paper impregnated with phenolic resin, often tan or brown.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] A PCB may be printed with a legend identifying the components, test points, or identifying text.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Originally, silkscreen printing was used for this purpose, but today other, finer quality printing methods are usually used.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Normally the legend does not affect the function of a PCBA.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] A printed circuit board can have multiple layers of copper which almost always are arranged in pairs.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The number of layers and the interconnection designed between them (vias, PTHs) provide a general estimate of the board complexity.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Using more layers allow for more routing options and better control of signal integrity, but are also time-consuming and costly to manufacture.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Likewise, selection of the vias for the board also allow fine tuning of the board size, escaping of signals off complex ICs, routing, and long term reliability, but are tightly coupled with production complexity and cost.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] One of the simplest boards to produce is the two-layer board.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] It has copper on both sides that are referred to as external layers; multi layer boards sandwich additional internal layers of copper and insulation.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] After two-layer PCBs, the next step up is the four-layer.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Only the outer layers need be coated; the inner copper layers are protected by the adjacent substrate layers.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] "Through hole" components are mounted by their wire leads passing through the board and soldered to traces on the other side.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] "Surface mount" components are attached by their leads to copper traces on the same side of the board.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] A board may use both methods for mounting components.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] PCBs with only through-hole mounted components are now uncommon.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Surface mounting is used for transistors, diodes, IC chips, resistors, and capacitors.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Through-hole mounting may be used for some large components such as electrolytic capacitors and connectors.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The first PCBs used through-hole technology, mounting electronic components by inserting leads through holes on one side of the board and soldering onto copper traces on the other side.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Boards may be single-sided, with an unplated component side, or more compact double-sided boards, with components soldered on both sides.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Leads may be soldered either manually or by a wave soldering machine.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Surface-mount technology emerged in the 1960s, gained momentum in the early 1980s, and became widely used by the mid-1990s.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Components were mechanically redesigned to have small metal tabs or end caps that could be soldered directly onto the PCB surface, instead of wire leads to pass through holes.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Components became much smaller and component placement on both sides of the board became more common than with through-hole mounting, allowing much smaller PCB assemblies with much higher circuit densities.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Surface mounting lends itself well to a high degree of automation, reducing labor costs and greatly increasing production rates compared with through-hole circuit boards.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Components can be supplied mounted on carrier tapes.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Surface mount components can be about one-quarter to one-tenth of the size and weight of through-hole components, and passive components much cheaper.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] However, prices of semiconductor surface mount devices (SMDs) are determined more by the chip itself than the package, with little price advantage over larger packages, and some wire-ended components, such as 1N4148 small-signal switch diodes, are actually significantly cheaper than SMD equivalents.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Each trace consists of a flat, narrow part of the copper foil that remains after etching.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Its resistance, determined by its width, thickness, and length, must be sufficiently low for the current the conductor will carry.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Power and ground traces may need to be wider than signal traces.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] In a multi-layer board one entire layer may be mostly solid copper to act as a ground plane for shielding and power return.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] For microwave circuits and high-speed digital signals (which use similar frequencies), transmission lines can be laid out in a planar form such as stripline or microstrip with carefully controlled dimensions to assure a consistent impedance.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] High density interconnects (HDI) PCBs have tracks or vias with a width or diameter of under 152 micrometers.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Laminates are manufactured by curing layers of cloth or paper with thermoset resin under pressure and heat to form an integral final piece of uniform thickness.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] They can be up to 4 by 8 feet (1.2 by 2.4 m) in width and length.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Varying cloth weaves (threads per inch or cm), cloth thickness, and resin percentage are used to achieve the desired final thickness and dielectric characteristics.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Available standard laminate thickness are listed in ANSI/IPC-D-275.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The cloth or fiber material used, resin material, and the cloth to resin ratio determine the laminate's type designation (FR-4, CEM-1, G-10, etc.) and therefore the characteristics of the laminate produced.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] There are quite a few different dielectrics that can be chosen to provide different insulating values depending on the requirements of the circuit.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Some of these dielectrics are polytetrafluoroethylene (Teflon), FR-4, FR-1, CEM-1 or CEM-3.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Thermal expansion is an important consideration especially with ball grid array (BGA) and naked die technologies, and glass fiber offers the best dimensional stability.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] FR-4 is by far the most common material used today.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The board stock with unetched copper on it is called "copper-clad laminate".
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] With decreasing size of board features and increasing frequencies, small non-homogeneities like uneven distribution of fiberglass or other filler, thickness variations, and bubbles in the resin matrix, and the associated local variations in the dielectric constant, are gaining importance.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The circuit-board substrates are usually dielectric composite materials.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The composites contain a matrix (usually an epoxy resin) and a reinforcement (usually a woven, sometimes non-woven, glass fibers, sometimes even paper), and in some cases a filler is added to the resin (e.g. ceramics; titanate ceramics can be used to increase the dielectric constant).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The reinforcement type defines two major classes of materials: woven and non-woven.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Woven reinforcements are cheaper, but the high dielectric constant of glass may not be favorable for many higher-frequency applications.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The spatially non-homogeneous structure also introduces local variations in electrical parameters, due to different resin/glass ratio at different areas of the weave pattern.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Non-woven reinforcements, or materials with low or no reinforcement, are more expensive but more suitable for some RF/analog applications.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] At the glass transition temperature the resin in the composite softens and significantly increases thermal expansion; exceeding Tg then exerts mechanical overload on the board components - e.g. the joints and the vias.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Below Tg the thermal expansion of the resin roughly matches copper and glass, above it gets significantly higher.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] As the reinforcement and copper confine the board along the plane, virtually all volume expansion projects to the thickness and stresses the plated-through holes.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Repeated soldering or other exposition to higher temperatures can cause failure of the plating, especially with thicker boards; thick boards therefore require a matrix with a high Tg.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The materials used determine the substrate's dielectric constant.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] This constant is also dependent on frequency, usually decreasing with frequency.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] As this constant determines the signal propagation speed, frequency dependence introduces phase distortion in wideband applications; as flat a dielectric constant vs frequency characteristics as is achievable is important here.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The impedance of transmission lines decreases with frequency, therefore faster edges of signals reflect more than slower ones.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Dielectric breakdown voltage determines the maximum voltage gradient the material can be subjected to before suffering a breakdown (conduction, or arcing, through the dielectric).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Tracking resistance determines how the material resists high voltage electrical discharges creeping over the board surface.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Loss tangent determines how much of the electromagnetic energy from the signals in the conductors is absorbed in the board material.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] This factor is important for high frequencies.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Choosing unnecessarily low-loss material is a common engineering error in high-frequency digital design; it increases the cost of the boards without a corresponding benefit.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Signal degradation by loss tangent and dielectric constant can be easily assessed by an eye pattern.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Moisture absorption occurs when the material is exposed to high humidity or water.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Both the resin and the reinforcement may absorb water; water also may be soaked by capillary forces through voids in the materials and along the reinforcement.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Epoxies of the FR-4 materials are not too susceptible, with absorption of only 0.15%.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Teflon has very low absorption of 0.01%.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Polyimides and cyanate esters, on the other side, suffer from high water absorption.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Absorbed water can lead to significant degradation of key parameters; it impairs tracking resistance, breakdown voltage, and dielectric parameters.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Relative dielectric constant of water is about 73, compared to about 4 for common circuit board materials.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Absorbed moisture can also vaporize on heating, as during soldering, and cause cracking and delamination, the same effect responsible for "popcorning" damage on wet packaging of electronic parts.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Careful baking of the substrates may be required to dry them prior to soldering.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Copper thickness of PCBs can be specified directly or as the weight of copper per area (in ounce per square foot) which is easier to measure.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] One ounce per square foot is 34 μm (0.0013 in) thickness.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] *Heavy copper* is a layer exceeding three ounces of copper per ft2, or approximately 105 μm (0.0041 in) thick.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Heavy copper layers are used for high current or to help dissipate heat.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] On the common FR-4 substrates, 1 oz copper per ft2 (35 μm (0.0014 in)) is the most common thickness; 2 oz (70 μm (0.0028 in)) and 0.5 oz (17.5 μm (0.00069 in)) thickness is often an option.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Flexible substrates typically have thinner metalization.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Metal-core boards for high power devices commonly use thicker copper; 35 μm (0.0014 in) is usual but also 140 μm (0.0055 in) and 400 μm (0.016 in) can be encountered.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] In the US, copper foil thickness is specified in units of ounces per square foot (oz/ft2), commonly referred to simply as *ounce*.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] 1/2 oz/ft2 foil is not widely used as a finished copper weight, but is used for outer layers when plating for through holes will increase the finished copper weight.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Some PCB manufacturers refer to 1 oz/ft2 copper foil as having a thickness of 35 μm (0.0014 in) (may also be referred to as 35 μ, 35 micron, or 35 mic).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit board manufacturing involves manufacturing bare printed circuit boards and then populating them with electronic components.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] In large-scale board manufacturing, multiple PCBs are grouped on a single panel for efficient processing.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] After assembly, they are separated (depaneled).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] A minimal PCB for a single component, used for prototyping, is called a **breakout board**.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The purpose of a breakout board is to "break out" the leads of a component on separate terminals so that manual connections to them can be made easily.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Breakout boards are especially used for surface-mount components or any components with fine lead pitch.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Advanced PCBs may contain components embedded in the substrate, such as capacitors and integrated circuits, to reduce the amount of space taken up by components on the surface of the PCB while improving electrical characteristics.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Multiwire is a patented technique of interconnection which uses machine-routed insulated wires embedded in a non-conducting matrix (often plastic resin).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] As of 2010, Multiwire is still available through Hitachi.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Corrections can be made to a Multiwire board layout more easily than to a PCB layout.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Before the advent of integrated circuits, *cordwood construction* allowed the highest possible component packing density.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The construction method was used with wire-ended components in applications where space was at a premium (such as fuzes, missile guidance, and telemetry systems) and in the high-speed computers of the day, where short traces were important.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] In cordwood construction, axial-leaded components were mounted between two parallel planes.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The name comes from the way axial-lead components (capacitors, resistors, coils, and diodes) are stacked in parallel rows and columns, like a stack of firewood.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] The components were either soldered together with jumper wire or they were connected to other components by thin nickel ribbon welded at right angles onto the component leads.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Some versions of cordwood construction used soldered single-sided PCBs as the interconnection method (as pictured), allowing the use of normal-leaded components at the cost of being difficult to remove the boards or replace any component that is not at the edge.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Cordwood construction was replaced with multi-layer board, SMD and ICs.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] A **Flexible Printed Circuit Board (FPCB)** is a thin, lightweight circuit made from flexible materials like polyimide.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] It can bend or fold while maintaining reliable electrical connections and is commonly used in compact electronic devices such as smartphones, wearables, and medical equipment.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit boards have been used as an alternative to their typical use for electronic and biomedical engineering thanks to the versatility of their layers, especially the copper layer.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Manufacturers may not support component-level repair of printed circuit boards because of the relatively low cost to replace compared with the time and cost of troubleshooting to a component level.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] In board-level repair, the technician identifies the board (PCA) on which the fault resides and replaces it.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] In many countries (including all European Single Market participants, the United Kingdom, Turkey, and China), legislation restricts the use of lead, cadmium, and mercury in electrical equipment.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] PCBs sold in such countries must therefore use lead-free manufacturing processes and lead-free solder, and attached components must themselves be compliant.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Safety Standard UL 796 covers component safety requirements for printed wiring boards for use as components in devices or appliances.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/printed-circuit-board] Testing analyzes characteristics such as flammability, maximum operating temperature, electrical tracking, heat deflection, and direct support of live electrical parts.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/solder-mask] Solder mask comes in different media depending upon the demands of the application.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/solder-mask] The lowest-cost solder mask is epoxy liquid that is silkscreened through the pattern onto the PCB.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/solder-mask] Other types are the liquid photoimageable solder mask (LPSM or LPI) inks and dry-film photoimageable solder mask (DFSM).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/solder-mask] LPSM can be silkscreened or sprayed on the PCB, exposed to the pattern and developed to provide openings in the pattern for parts to be soldered to the copper pads.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/solder-mask] DFSM is vacuum-laminated on the PCB then exposed and developed.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/solder-mask] All three processes typically go through a thermal cure of some type after the pattern is defined although LPI solder masks are also available in ultraviolet (UV) cure.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/solder-mask] The solder stop layer on a flexible board is also called *coverlay* or *coverfilm*.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/solder-mask] In electronic design automation, the solder mask is treated as part of the layer stack of the printed circuit board, and is described in individual Gerber files for the top and bottom side of the PCB like any other layer (such as the copper and silk-screen layers).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] An SMT component is usually smaller than its through-hole counterpart because it has either smaller leads or no leads at all.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] It may have short pins or leads of various styles, flat contacts, a matrix of solder balls (BGAs), or terminations on the body of the component.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Surface-mount technology was developed in the 1960s.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] By 1986, surface-mounted components accounted for 10% of the market at most but were rapidly gaining popularity.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] By the late 1990s, the great majority of high-tech electronic printed circuit assemblies were dominated by surface mount devices.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Much of the pioneering work in this technology was done by IBM.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] The design approach first demonstrated by IBM in 1960 in a small-scale computer was later applied in the Launch Vehicle Digital Computer used in the Instrument Unit that guided all Saturn IB and Saturn V vehicles.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Components were mechanically redesigned to have small metal tabs or end caps that could be directly soldered to the surface of the PCB.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Components became much smaller, and component placement on both sides of a board became far more common with surface mounting than through-hole mounting, allowing much higher circuit densities and smaller circuit boards and, in turn, machines or subassemblies containing the boards.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Often, the surface tension of the solder is enough to hold the parts to the board; in rare cases, parts on the bottom or "second" side of the board may be secured with adhesive to keep components from dropping off inside reflow ovens.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Adhesive is sometimes used to hold SMT components on the bottom side of a board if a wave soldering process is used to solder both SMT and through-hole components simultaneously.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Surface mounting lends itself well to a high degree of automation, reducing labor cost and greatly increasing production rates.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Conversely, SMT does not lend itself well to manual or low-automation fabrication, which is more economical and faster for one-off prototyping and small-scale production; this is one reason why many through-hole components are still manufactured.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Some SMDs can be soldered with a temperature-controlled manual soldering iron, but those that are very small or have too fine a lead pitch are often almost impossible to manually solder without expensive equipment.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Different terms describe the components, technique, and machines used in manufacturing.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Where components are to be placed, the printed circuit board normally has flat, usually tin-lead, silver, or gold plated copper pads without holes, called *solder pads*.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Solder paste, a sticky mixture of flux and tiny solder particles, is first applied to all the solder pads with a stainless steel or nickel stencil using a screen printing process.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] It can also be applied by a jet-printing mechanism, similar to an inkjet printer.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] After pasting, the boards proceed to the pick-and-place machines, where they are placed on a conveyor belt.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] The components to be placed on the boards are usually delivered to the production line in either paper/plastic tapes wound on reels or plastic tubes.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Some large integrated circuits are delivered in static-free trays.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Numerical control pick-and-place machines remove the parts from the tapes, tubes or trays and place them on the PCB.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] The boards are then conveyed into the reflow soldering oven.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] They first enter a pre-heat zone, where the temperature of the board and all the components is gradually, uniformly raised to prevent thermal shock.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] The boards then enter a zone where the temperature is high enough to melt the solder particles in the solder paste, bonding the component leads to the pads on the circuit board.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] The surface tension of the molten solder helps keep the components in place.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] If the solder pad geometries are correctly designed, surface tension automatically aligns the components on their pads.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] There are a number of *techniques* for reflowing solder.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] One is to use infrared lamps; this is called infrared reflow.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Another technology that is becoming popular again is special fluorocarbon liquids with high boiling points which use a method called vapor phase reflow.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Due to environmental concerns, this method was falling out of favor until lead-free legislation was introduced which requires tighter controls on soldering.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] At the end of 2008, convection soldering was the most popular reflow technology using either standard air or nitrogen gas.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Each method has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] With infrared reflow, the board designer must lay the board out so that short components do not fall into the shadows of tall components.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Component location is less restricted if the designer knows that vapor phase reflow or convection soldering will be used in production.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Following reflow soldering, certain irregular or heat-sensitive components may be installed and soldered by hand, or in large-scale automation, by focused infrared beam (FIB) or localized convection equipment.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] If the circuit board is double-sided then this printing, placement, reflow process may be repeated using either solder paste or glue to hold the components in place.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] If a wave soldering process is used, then the parts must be glued to the board before processing to prevent them from floating off when the solder paste holding them in place is melted.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] After soldering, the boards may be washed to remove flux residues and any stray solder balls that could short out closely spaced component leads.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Rosin flux is removed with fluorocarbon solvents, high flash point hydrocarbon solvents, or low flash solvents e.g. limonene (derived from orange peels) which require extra rinsing or drying cycles.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Water-soluble fluxes are removed with deionized water and detergent, followed by an air blast to quickly remove residual water.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] However, most electronic assemblies are made using a "No-Clean" process where the flux residues are designed to be left on the circuit board, since they are considered harmless.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] This saves the cost of cleaning, speeds up the manufacturing process, and reduces waste.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] However, it is generally suggested to wash the assembly, even when a "No-Clean" process is used, when the application uses very high frequency clock signals (in excess of 1 GHz).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Another reason to remove no-clean residues is to improve adhesion of conformal coatings and underfill materials.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Certain manufacturing standards, such as those written by the IPC – Association Connecting Electronics Industries require cleaning regardless of the solder flux type used to ensure a thoroughly clean board.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Proper cleaning removes all traces of solder flux, as well as dirt and other contaminants that may be invisible to the naked eye.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] No-Clean or other soldering processes may leave "white residues" that, according to IPC, are acceptable "provided that these residues have been qualified and documented as benign".
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] However, while shops conforming to IPC standards are expected to adhere to the Association's rules on board condition, not all manufacturing facilities apply IPC standards, nor are they required to do so.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Additionally, in some applications, such as low-end electronics, such stringent manufacturing methods are excessive both in expense and time required.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Finally, the boards are visually inspected for missing or misaligned components and solder bridging.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] If needed, they are sent to a rework station where a human operator repairs any errors.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] They are then usually sent to the testing stations (in-circuit testing and/or functional testing) to verify that they operate correctly.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Automated optical inspection (AOI) systems are commonly used in PCB manufacturing.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] This technology has proven highly efficient for process improvements and quality achievements.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Defective surface-mount components can be repaired by using soldering irons (for some connections) or a non-contact rework system.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] In most cases, a rework system is the better choice because SMD work with a soldering iron requires considerable skill and is not always feasible.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Sometimes hundreds or thousands of the same part need to be repaired.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] If due to assembly, such errors are often caught during the process.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] However, a whole new level of rework arises when component failure is discovered too late, and perhaps unnoticed until the end user of the device being manufactured experiences it.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Rework can also be used if products of sufficient value to justify it require revision or re-engineering, perhaps to change a single firmware-based component.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Reworking in large volumes requires an operation designed for that purpose.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] There are essentially two non-contact soldering/desoldering methods: infrared soldering and soldering with hot gas.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] With infrared soldering, the energy for heating up the solder joint is transmitted by long-, medium- or short-wave infrared electromagnetic radiation.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] During hot gas soldering, the energy for heating up the solder joint is transmitted by a hot gas.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] This can be air or inert gas (nitrogen).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Surface-mount components are usually smaller than their counterparts with leads, and are designed to be handled by machines rather than by humans.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] The electronics industry has standardized package shapes and sizes (the leading standardisation body is JEDEC).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] For 5% precision SMD resistors usually are marked with their resistance values using three digits: two significant digits and a multiplier digit.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] These are quite often white lettering on a black background, but other colored backgrounds and lettering can be used.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] For 1% precision SMD resistors, the code is used, as three digits would otherwise not convey enough information.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] of values, while the letter indicates the multiplier.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Non-electrolytic capacitors are usually unmarked and the only reliable method of determining their value is removal from the circuit and subsequent measurement with a capacitance meter or impedance bridge.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] The materials used to fabricate the capacitors, such as nickel tantalate, possess different colours and these can give an approximate idea of the capacitance of the component.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Generally physical size is proportional to capacitance and voltage for the same dielectric.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] For example, a 100 nF, 50 V capacitor may come in the same package as a 10 nF, 150 V device.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] SMD (non-electrolytic) capacitors, which are usually monolithic ceramic capacitors, exhibit the same body color on all four faces not covered by the end caps.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Smaller inductance with moderately high current ratings are usually of the ferrite bead type.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] They are simply a metal conductor looped through a ferrite bead and almost the same as their through-hole versions but possess SMD end caps rather than leads.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] They appear dark grey and are magnetic, unlike capacitors with a similar dark grey appearance.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] (nH) range and are often used as power supply rail decouplers or in high frequency parts of a circuit.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Larger inductors and transformers may of course be through-hole mounted on the same board.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] SMT inductors with larger inductance values often have turns of wire or flat strap around the body or embedded in clear epoxy, allowing the wire or strap to be seen.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] These higher inductance types are often limited to small current ratings, although some of the flat strap types can handle a few amps.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] As with capacitors, component values and identifiers for smaller inductors are not usually marked on the component itself; if not documented or printed on the PCB, measurement, usually removed from the circuit, is the only way of determining them.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Larger inductors, especially wire-wound types in larger footprints, usually have the value printed on the top.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Discrete semiconductors, such as diodes and transistors are often marked with a two- or three-symbol code.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] The same code marked on different packages or on devices from different manufacturers can translate to different devices.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] Many of these codes, used because the devices are too small to be marked with more traditional numbers used on larger packages, correlate to more familiar traditional part numbers when a correlation list is consulted.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/surface-mount-technology] is also available, although these lists are not complete.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] A **via** (Latin, 'path' or 'way') is an electrical connection between two or more metal layers of a printed circuit boards (PCB) or integrated circuit.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] Essentially a via is a small drilled hole that goes through two or more adjacent layers; the hole is plated with metal (often copper) that forms an electrical connection through the insulating layers.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] Vias are an important concern in PCB manufacturing.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] As vertical structures crossing multiple layers, they are specified differently from most of the design, which increases the chance for errors.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] They place the strictest demands on registration (how closely aligned different layers are).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] They are manufactured with different tooling from other features -- tooling that typically has looser tolerances.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] If either the hole or any layer is slightly out of place, the wrong electrical connections may be made; this may not be visible from the surface.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] After the hole is drilled, it must also be lined with conductive material, as opposed to simply leaving conductive material in place on copper layers.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] Even an initially good board may develop problems later because the via reacts to heat differently from the substrate around it.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] Vias also represent a discontinuity in the electrical impedance, which can cause problems for signal integrity.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] In printed circuit board (PCB) design, a via consists of two pads in corresponding positions on different copper layers of the board, that are electrically connected by a hole through the board.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] The hole is made conductive by electroplating, or is lined with a tube or a rivet.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] High-density multilayer PCBs may have microvias: **blind vias** are exposed only on one side of the board, while **buried vias** connect internal layers without being exposed on either surface.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] **Thermal vias** carry heat away from power devices and are typically used in arrays of about a dozen.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] A via, sometimes called PTV or plated-through-via, should not be confused with a plated through hole (PTH).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] A via is used as an interconnection between copper layers on a PCB while the PTH is generally made larger than vias and is used as a plated hole for acceptance of component leads - such as non-SMT resistors, capacitors, and DIP package IC.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] PTH can also be used as holes for mechanical connection while vias may not.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] Three major kinds of vias are shown in right figure.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] The basic steps of making a PCB are: making the substrate material and stacking it in layers; through-drilling of plating the vias; and copper trace patterning using photolithography and etching.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] With this standard procedure, possible via configurations are limited to through-holes.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] Depth-controlled drilling techniques such as using lasers can allow for more varied via types.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] Laser drills can also be used for smaller and more precisely positioned holes than mechanical drills produce.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] PCB manufacturing typically starts with a so-called core, a basic double-sided PCB.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] Layers beyond the first two are stacked from this basic building block.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] If two more layers are consecutively stacked from bottom of core, you can have a 1-2 via, a 1-3 via and a through hole.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] Each type of via is made by drilling at each stacking stage.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] If one layer is stacked on top of the core and other is stacked from the bottom, the possible via configurations are 1-3, 2-3 and through hole.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] The user must gather information about the PCB manufacturer's allowed methods of stacking and possible vias.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] For cheaper boards, only through holes are made and antipad (or clearance) is placed on layers which are supposed not to be contacted to vias.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] If well made, PCB vias will primarily fail due to differential expansion and contraction between the copper plating and the PCB in the out of plane direction (Z).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] This differential expansion and contraction will induce cyclic fatigue in the copper plating, eventually resulting in crack propagation and an electrical open circuit.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] Various design, material, and environmental parameters will influence the rate of this degradation.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] To ensure via robustness, IPC sponsored a round-robin exercise that developed a time to failure calculator.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] In integrated circuit (IC) design, a via is a small opening in an insulating oxide layer that allows a conductive connection between different layers.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] A via on an integrated circuit that passes completely through a silicon wafer or die is called a through-chip via or through-silicon via (TSV).
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] **Through-glass vias** (**TGV**) have been studied by Corning Glass for semiconductor packaging, due to the reduced electrical loss of glass versus silicon packaging.
[src:pcb-layout-embedded/via-electronics] A via connecting the lowest layer of metal to diffusion or poly is typically called a "contact".
